[1] Jamaica
Date: Tue 15 Jan 2008
Source: The Jamaica Observer [edited]
<http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/html/20080114T190000-0500_131405_OBS_DENGUE_CLAIMS_TEEN_IN_ST_JAMES_.asp>

The deadly dengue haemorrhagic fever claimed the life of a 16 year old girl
at the weekend, igniting fears of an outbreak in Mount Salem, one of this
resort's most depressed inner-city communities.
A student of the Caribbean Christian Centre for the deaf died at the
Cornwall Regional Hospital between Friday and Saturday [11-12 Jan 2008]
after all her vital organs collapsed under the pressure of the viral
illness, which is transmitted by the female _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito. "This
death highlights a looming crisis which could have incalculable costs if it
goes unresolved," said councillor Avery Rose-Green (PNP, Mount Salem
division) in reference to the deplorable hygienic conditions that
characterise the area.
Mount Salem, a paradoxical division featuring a curious mix of affluence
and abject poverty, is home to hundreds of residents who have no access to
basic social amenities such as flush toilets. Consequently, they engage in
a dangerous practice -- known as parachuting -- whereby they defecate in
plastic (lada) bags and throw them into the large uncovered drains, which
run through several sections of the community. This, coupled with irregular
garbage collection, facilitates the breeding of mosquitoes, heightening the
risk to pubic health. Officials from the St James Health Department were
locked in meetings up to press time yesterday and were consequently unable
to comment.
[byline: Pat Roxborough-Wright]
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett
[The accumulation of water-holding objects in garbage may contribute to
breeding sites of _Aedes aegypti_, but the disposal of human excrement into
open drains would not. A map showing the location of St James in Jamaica
can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/jamaica_pol_2002.jpg>. - Mod.TY]
