[3] Costa Rica
Date: Sat 26 Jan 2008
Source: Milenio [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.milenio.com/index.php/2008/01/25/182623/>

According to the daily newspaper La Nacion, the CCSS [Costa Rican Social
Security] detected at the end of last year 3 Costa Ricans who were infected
[with dengue virus], who had entered the country from Panama. The
epidemiological fence was ordered by the CCSS in the southern zone of the
country, along the Panamanian border, to impede the propagation of dengue
[virus] type 3 here [in Costa Rica].
The CCSS, which administers state hospitals in Costa Rica, established the
epidemiological fence in this zone since dengue virus type 3 has not been
registered in the country but has been present in Panama, according to the
newspaper.
The epidemiological fence cut off the dissemination of dengue [virus type]
3, said Costa Rican minister of health, Maria Luisa Avila, pointing out
that detection of these cases occurred at the end of December [2007]. She
indicated that "the appearance of a new type -- dengue virus 3 -- increases
the risk of people susceptible to the development of DHF.
The Minister informed [the newspaper] that "Panama Ministry of Health
officials, which visited the country to inspect the condition of the
indigenous [people] who work here, took advantage of this visit to
cooperate with Costa Rican authorities concerning dengue."
According to official data, dengue, following its eradication in Costa
Rica, reappeared -- as variants [dengue viruses] 1 and 2 -- in just last
year affected 25 000 people, 8 of whom died, including 4 minors.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is an excellent example of inter-country cooperation to achieve
disease surveillance and control. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map
