[4] Colombia
Date: Sat 26 Jan 2008
Source: Prensa Latina [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.prensalatina.com.mx/Article.asp?ID=%7B352DF4B8-557D-440B-BB20-78CC15DD7216%7D&language=ES>

Worrisome increase of dengue cases in Colombia
----------------------------------------------
The National Institute of Health considers the increase of dengue cases in
Colombia to be worrying, despite the preventive and educational campaigns
carried out by health officials.
Data from this institution indicate that last year [2007] there was a 10
per cent increase in the number of cases, which represents 3694 illnesses
more than in 2006. In that year [2006] 38 842 cases were reported in the
country and in 2007 there were 42 536 reported according to Pilar Zambrano,
epidemiologist with the National Institute of Health.
In press releases, this official said that the zones most affected by the
presence of the dengue [virus] mosquito vector were the cities of Yopal,
Medellin, Cucuta, Villavicencio, Valledupar, Santa Marta, and Cartagena.
However, she pointed out that despite the increase in the number of
infected people, the numbers of deaths were reduced, which were more than
50 in 2006 and only 19 last year [2007].
--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Apparently this year (2008), as with some previous ones (1998, for
example), is becoming a pandemic year [for dengue], at least in Latin
America. - Mod.LJS
Ironically, Colombia essentially eliminated _Aedes aegypti_ by the 1960s,
after which this mosquito reinvaded the coastal areas and spread into the
inter-Andean valleys and cities, such as Medellin, that had not had this
mosquito and are now infested with this dengue virus vector.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Colombia can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=3.9,-73.1,5>. - Mod.TY]
