[5] Ecuador: (El Oro)
Date: Sat 26 Jan 2007
Source: Diario La Opinion [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.diariopinion.com/primeraPlana/verArticulo.php?id=36767>

The number of possible dengue cases in El Oro has increased to 55 from the
beginning of the year [2008] up until Tuesday of this week [ 22 Jan 2008].
The majority of these [cases] were located in Santa Rosa and Machala, which
presumes more than 2 per day.
Taking into account the underreporting of the disease, recognizing that
many people opt for self-medication and the uncertainty of the diagnosis,
those affected [infected by dengue virus] could be many more [than those
reported]. It is estimated that for every "official" case, 3 are
unreported. Moreover, [dengue case] figures are those reported by state
health units and do not include those who are treated in private [facilities].
However, the director of health, Rosa Marina Aguilar, pointed out that of
the 55 cases reported [as dengue] by the health areas, only 3 have been
[laboratory] confirmed by the Instituto de Higiene Izquieta Perez.
The rest [of the reported dengue cases] are presumptive or probable, taking
into account their fevers, the official explained, while explaining that
the heads [of the health units] are pushing initiatives aimed at dealing
with the disease and to reduce its incidence.
He noted that the contingency plan turns on 4 actions: prevention sustained
by community education, cleanup, fumigation in areas of risk [of
transmission], and abate application [larvicidal treatment]. Aguilar
underscored that the task was not just that of the National Malaria
Eradication Service, but also involved the active participation of the
teams for basic [medical] attention.
He then signaled that in the case of cleanup he hoped to count on the
collaboration of the armed forces and the municipalities, indicating the
importance of community participation. He especially referred to
cooperation in the destruction of objects in houses, which accumulate
water, which turn into mosquito breeding sites for larvae of _Aedes
aegypti_ , the vector of the disease [virus].
It is worth remembering that last year [2007] there were more than 1600
[dengue] cases, of which 114 corresponded to the classical type, the most
dangerous variety [this number must mean DHF, rather than classical dengue
fever. - Mod.TY]
As a positive fact, it is [important ] to point out that there have been no
deaths, thanks to opportune detection of complications and adequate
treatment, Dr Aguilar emphasized.
--
