[6] Venezuela: (Caracas)
Date: Thu 24 Jan 2008
Source: Noticiero Venevision [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://noticiero.venevision.net/index_not.asp?id_noticia=20080124001104&id_seccion=04>

Clinics and hospitals in Caracas continue to register an increasing number
of patients infected with dengue [virus]. This worries physicians because
the number [of dengue cases] is greater than in previous years. According
to the Venezuelan Society of Infectious Diseases [Sociedad Venezolana de
Infectologia], 2007 had the greatest number of dengue cases registered
since the epidemic in the country in 1989.
The official statistics for 2008 to date do not indicate if the disease
continues to increase [as detected in] emergency rooms and health centers.
Experts consider that it is necessary that official epidemiological
bulletins be published so that health officials can react in a timely
fashion and fight the disease.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It is not clear why publication of the official epidemiological bulletins
was stopped in the middle of last year (2007). Although information about
dengue in Venezuela is coming out piecemeal, it is evident that dengue has
been a significant problem there from 2007 until the present, as it has
been in many parts of Central and South America. Jose Felix Oletta, former
minister of Health and Social Assistance, indicated in an article in El
Nacional of 25 Jan 2008 (<http://www.el-nacional.com/www/site/>) that he
had calculated from figures published in the national press that at least
42 people died of dengue in 2007 with 82 000 cases of the disease. He said
that there were 18 deaths just in the Libertador municipality, no fewer
than 5 Mianda state, 6 in Aragua, 2 in Carabobo, and 9 in Zulia.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Venezuela can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=7.1,-66.2,5>. - Mod.TY]
