[8] Venezuela: (Zulia)
Date: Sun 27 Jan 2008
Source: Ojo Pelao [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.ojopelao.com/diarios1.php?id=14590>

The team of specialists who warned of the possible existence of a dengue
[virus] serotype 5 confirmed yesterday [26 Jan 2008] that national and
regional authorities must investigate thoroughly why there are complicated
cases with liver damage. Jorge Guerrero, one of the doctors involved in the
study, spearheaded the application. "We request that doctor Ferdinando
Letbrandi, head of the biology lab and mutation of viruses of the
Venezuelan Institute of Scientific Research (IVIC), be sent all the
evidence to determine whether or not there is a new dengue virus," said the
doctor from Zulia.
Up to the end of 2007, there were nearly 19 000 cases in the region. So far
this year [2008], 1291 [dengue cases have been] reported, according to the
Ministry of Health. They complain that health authorities in the region
hide epidemiological figures.
The certification of the probable existence of serotype 5 of the dengue
virus was called for yesterday the doctors from Zulia, who reported on
Monday [21 Jan 2008] of the presence of a new dengue virus strain in the
population.
"We have had patients with severe levels of liver and lung injury, [and
with] gallbladder and kidney problems. Given the suspicion caused by this
situation we notified the Ministry of Health and now ask that samples be
taken from patients who are in hospitals. "We have great confidence that
IVIC, through the Ministry of Health, will determine whether or not a new
dengue virus exists," he said.
The upsurge of dengue fever has caused alarm in the region due to the high
figures reported by the Ministry of People's Power for Health (MPSS) from
the last quarter of 2007.
"We are witnessing an epidemic that over the years, instead of decreasing,
has grown at significant levels in Zulia and in other states around the
country," added the University of Zulia School of Medicine Rector Leonardo
Atencio.
Nereida Valero, head of dengue research and head of the virology laboratory
of the Institute of Clinical Research, said that in this instance they have
no evidence to justify the presence of a new dengue [virus] serotype. "The
molecular studies of dengue virus have shown that there are 4 serotypes,
and it is highly unlikely that a mutation occurred, or a change in its
genome, [sufficient] to produce a new serotype. Until we do detailed study
of isolation and sequencing of the virus, we can not talk of a new
serotype," he said.
The virologist confirmed the circulation of all 4 serotypes of dengue
[virus] in the population, and that last year [2007] they had identified
them. Until now, IVIC has not received the samples to scientifically
analyze the probability of the emergence of a dengue [virus] serotype 5.
Despite suspicions by the clinical doctors in Zulia, Letbrandi assured that
the studies conducted as of the end of 2007 had not found another strain,
"but did not rule out that there could be a mutated virus (in nature) with
a touch more severe hepatic [symptoms] than normal."
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The situation in Zulia illustrates the need for timely laboratory support
for accurate diagnosis, especially when clinicians believe that they are
seeing an unusual set of symptoms. Concluding that there is a new dengue
virus serotype based only in clinical signs is premature. Fortunately, the
virologist involved here is clearly doubtful that a new dengue virus
serotype has emerged during the Zulia epidemic. ProMED-mail awaits with
interest any news concerning the sequence and antigenic test results as
they emerge. - Mod.TY]
