[9] Venezuela: (national)
Date: Sun 27 Jan 2007
Source: Ojo Pelao [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.ojopelao.com/diarios1.php?id=12812>

The number of people in Zulia ill [with dengue] went from 8181 in 2006 to
18 405 in all of 2007. [Nationally], there were 77 269 cases of classical
dengue and DHF in 2007, an increase of 94 per cent, which makes this an
epidemic, according to a report from the Ministry of People's Power for
Health. [Cases] of this disease in Zulia represent 24 per cent of the
national total. The regional increase [in dengue cases] was 125 per cent.
The World Health Organization considers that [this increase] is due to the
El Nino [climatological] phenomenon.
According to data provided by the Director General of Epidemiology, Zulia
leads the country in the number of [dengue] cases, a marked difference from
other states as follows: Miranda (5584 cases), Guarico (4938), and
Anzoategui (4419). All of these are considered in an epidemic state
according to the Ministry [of Health].
The presence of diverse [dengue virus] serotypes in the region increases
the risk of outbreaks of DHF, of which Zulia has the greatest number: 1346
cases of a national total of 6145.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There are some discrepancies in the numbers of Venezuelan dengue cases
cited in the articles above. However, it is quite clear that Venezuela
experienced a major dengue epidemic in 2007, and that it appears to be
continuing into 2008. - Mod.TY]
