[10] Bolivia: (Chapare Region, Cochabamba)
Date: Fri 25 Jan 2008
Source: Los Tiempos, Bolivian Information Agency (ABI) report [in Spanish,
trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.lostiempos.com/noticias/25-01-08/25_01_08_ultimas_nac8.php>

The Vice Minister of Health, Juan Alberto Nogales, indicated this Friday
[25 Jan 2008] that the [dengue] epidemics which occurred in [the] Chapare
[region], (Cochabamba) [department which is equivalent to a state or
province. - Mod.TY] are controlled and under observation.
"Epidemic outbreaks have appeared as a consequence of flooding, are under
surveillance and we are developing all strategic technical measures in
order to calm the people," he indicated.
A national emergency alert was declared, accompanied by a national sanitary
alert, which implicated designation of funds, materials and deployment of
activities aimed at avoiding the consequences of the floods.
He indicated that in the Chapare they were developing a campaign centered
on the eradication of the mosquito that causes [transmits the virus] that
causes dengue. He indicated that this work is being done with the
Department of Health of Cochabamba, in order to eradicate dengue in the
Chapare zone. "We have help from departmental teams for [field] studies of
mosquito proliferation, as well as the collaboration of 10 Cuban
entomologists, who are carrying out a thorough surveillance in order to
calm the populace," he assured [everyone].
Given this, he said that in the previous week [week of 13 Jan 2008] 101
cases of classical dengue were registered, and there were 143 cases in the
entire country. Also, he said that new hantavirus cases and 10 malaria
cases are being treated and controlled. "Despite the magnitude of these
happenings, we are able to control outbreak of these infections," Nogales
mentioned.
--
