[12] Brazil: (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Mon 21 Jan 2008
Source: O Globo Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/rio/mat/2008/01/21/reaparecimento_do_tipo_2_do_virus_da_dengue_pode_ter_aumentado_internacoes_pela_doenca-328119875.asp>

The reappearance of dengue virus type 2 is now beginning to become a source
of worry for the municipal Secretary of Health. According to the
superintendent of epidemiology of the Secretariat, Meri Baran, the number
of [hospital] admissions due to dengue has increased since 2007.
Previously, few were admitted, but an increase has been seen in 2007,
principally of children. There is a hypothesis that this increase occurred
with the appearance of dengue [virus] type 2, which practically was not
recorded since 2002, when there was a surge of [dengue virus] type 3, she said.
According to Meri Baran, this increase in admissions is principally among
people who have had the disease before.
The superintendent of the Secretariat, however, denied that Rio is having a
dengue epidemic. According to her, this only occurs with the emergence of a
new virus serotype, as was the case in 2002, the year in which Rio had its
greatest epidemic of the disease [caused by serotype 3 replacing types 1 &
2. - Mod.JW].
There is a remote possibility of a dengue epidemic due to the appearance of
dengue [virus] type 4 in Brazil. The threat of dengue [virus] type 4 always
exists because it has circulated in other countries, but has not entered
Brazil. There has been just one [dengue virus type 4] case, in the
beginning of the 1990s, in Rondonia [far western Brazil], but did not
become disseminated.
At the beginning of this month [January 2008] the state Secretariat of
Health said that Rio was the city that had the greatest index of dengue
virus infections in the state in 2007, registering around 23 000 cases.
Niteroi [directly across the bay from Rio] was in 2nd place with more than
7000 infected [individuals], followed by Sao Goncalo, Campos dos
Goytacazes, Itaperuna, and Macae.
[byline: Luisa Valle]
--
