[13] Brazil: (Ceara)
Date: Sun 26 Jan 2008
Source: Diario do Nordeste [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://diariodonordeste.globo.com:80/materia.asp?Codigo=507079>

The numbers of classical dengue cases confirmed by the state Secretariat of
Health (SESA) has practically quadrupled. There are 140 new registered
cases and the number confirmed by the Secretariat has risen from 52 to 192.
This information is from the weekly dengue bulletin issued by the
Epidemiological Surveillance Nucleus of SESA.
According to the bulletin, from 1 Jan [2008] to the present, there has been
notification of 458 suspected dengue cases in 58 municipalities. Of these,
192 cases were laboratory confirmed in 20.6 per cent of municipalities in
Ceara.
As of 18 [Jan 2008] the number of notified suspected dengue cases was 141
in 38 municipalities. Excluding 58 samples considered negative, there were
52 laboratory confirmed cases in 15 municipalities, 11 suspected DHF
[cases], and 20 others not classified. There has also been an increase in
the number of suspected DHF cases, which are in the process of being
investigated epidemiologically.
As for the past week [week of 20 Jan 2008], the Secretariat counted 11
[cases], and yesterday SESA reported 23. The numbers of reported cases in
the municipalities, in decreasing order, are: 16 in Fortaleza, 4 in
Caucaia, one in Aracoiaba, another in Redencao, and one also in Sao Goncalo
do Amarante.
[byline: Ludmila Wanbergna]
--
communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Ceara has been particularly affected by dengue and, by the way, not only
by dengue, but also by cholera. - Mod.LJS]
