[15] Philippines: (national)
Date: Wed 23 Jan 2008
Source: Google-Sina Medical health articles [edited]
<http://google-sina.com/2008/01/23/dengue-cases-surge-in-philippines/>

Health officials recorded an alarming increase of cases in the first 12
days of the year [2008] as 5 people died from dengue in the Philippines,
local press reported on Tuesday [22 Jan 2008].
Dengue cases recorded at the San Lazaro Hospital in Manila have piled up to
380 from 1-12 Jan [2008], a 211 per cent increase compared to the same
period last year, local TV network ABS-CBN News reported, citing Eric
Tayag, chief of the Philippine National Epidemiology Center of the
Department of Health (DOH). The San Lazaro Hospital is the main medical
facility that takes in dengue cases from all over Metro Manila, capital
region of the country. Tayag said that of the 380 cases, 5 have already
died. The health official said the number could rise as the DOH has yet to
check other hospitals in Metro Manila.
"What's alarming is the increase of dengue cases as early as (this month
[January 2008]) in Metro Manila areas compared to last year," he said. The
official said that due to the alarming increase in dengue cases, the DOH
has decided to launch an anti-dengue drive this month. Tayag said that as
early as this month [January 2008], hospitals in Metro Manila may put up
express lanes in anticipation of dengue victims to pour into medical
facilities this month.
Tayag said the increase in dengue cases in Metro Manila can be attributed
to the abnormal weather conditions in the country. He mentioned that
dengue-carrying mosquitoes could have been spreading because of the rain
showers in the past few days.
The health official reminded parents to immediately take their children to
hospitals for checkup once they catch fever or show early signs of dengue.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Brent Barrett
******
[16] Saudi Arabia: (Jeddah)
Date: Wed 23 Jan 2008
Source: Arab News [edited]
http://www.arabnews.com/?page=1§ion=0&article=105990&d=23&m=1&y=2008&pix=kingdom.jpg&category=Kingdom

Health officials in Jeddah registered 16 confirmed cases of dengue fever
this month [January 2008]. A total of 342 cases of the illness were
detected last year [2007], according to a source at the Health Affairs
Administration in Jeddah on Monday, Al-Eqtisadiah daily reported yesterday
[Tue 22 Jan 2008]. The spread of dengue has been linked to standing water,
which is more prevalent in the winter months. Residences that have standing
water in cisterns are also at risk of spreading dengue.
Dr Nabeel Abu Khutwah, a specialist on environmental science at the King
Abdul Aziz University and a consultant at the Jeddah Mayor's Office, said
that all the detected cases of dengue fever were treated and healed. "While
the laboratory under the Jeddah Mayor's Office detected 21 varieties of
mosquitoes, it also found that the 2nd most common variety in the area was
the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito which carries the dengue virus," Abu Khutwah said.
The scientist observed a sharp reduction in the disease last year [2007]
compared to 2006 when the number of registered cases was 1314. He did not
attribute any death to the disease in 2007. However he noted that an
average of 8.2 cases were reported over the last 5 weeks of 2007 while the
weekly average in the 5 weeks previous to it was 3.4.
--
